Item: Ralph Meijer: FOSDEM 2007 Jabber devroom schedule published
<http://ralphm.net/blog/2007/02/09/fosdem_2007_devroom>
Date: 2007-02-09 15:49:30 UTC
Back in November I[1] posted[2] a call for presence (haha) for the Jabber developer room[3] at FOSDEM 2007. But this year, with the help of Peter Saint-André[4], the hunt for speakers has been far more aggressive than previous editions. I must say that this has resulted in a great, packed, line-up and I am sure that many people (currently) from outside the will be interested in what will be presented. Loki has put the schedule online earlier today.

To give a quick overview, on Saturday Peter will kick off with a Jabber 101[5], targetted at getting developers acquainted with Jabber technologies. Heiner Wolf follows with a presentation on Virtual Presence[6], a way to meet up on webpages. Ian Paterson will try to reach the Rich Internet Application crowd that now uses JSON, Comet or AJAX for browser-server communications, and show how you can put XMPP to use[7] in this arena. The day is concluded by two presentations on the Tigase server implentation: Artur Hefczyc will talk[8] on Tigase itself and Diana Cionoiu will explain[9] how Yate hooks up Jingle with Tigase to build tomorrow's open telephony networks.

For those that manage to get up bright and early on Sunday morning, I will let visiting developers dig[10] right into what Peter has touched upon the day before. Using Twisted[11], I will explain how to actually develop asynchronous applications that communicate using XMPP and act as a Jabber client or server-side component. Then this session will transform into a mini-sprint and the visitors will rattle their keyboards to crunch out running Python code. Bring your own laptops!

Around lunch we give[12] Robert McQueen and Peter a Jingle to get us up to speed on rich media streaming, and proceed with Mickaël Rémond of ejabberd fame on OneTeam[13], a Mozilla/XUL based Jabber client application. Mika Raento takes us to the mobile world with his talk on Jaiku[14], that combines rich presence and group messaging on the web and on the mobile. Then we close the room to go Peter Saint-André's talk in the huge Janson room on secure communications[15]. Be sure to check out the interview[16]. To allow for some extra time for answering questions after that talk, we reopen the developers' room for a Q&A[17] session, and possibly a few 5 min. lightning talks, and then close up shop.

